Geographical factors found to be associated with vaccination coverage are: residence, area, poverty index and elevation (Table 3). Contrary to vaccination completeness, urban areas had lower odds of achieving vaccination coverage compared to rural areas (0.73, 95% CI: 0.65—0.82). Similar to vaccination completeness, higher poverty levels were associated with increased odds of achieving vaccination coverage (1.10, 95% CI: 1.06—1.14); and higher elevations were associated with lower odds of achieving vaccination coverage (0.94, 95% CI: 0.91—0.97). We further found that larger geographical areas had lower odds of achieving vaccination coverage (0.97, 95% CI: 0.94—0.99). We also found a strong spatial pattern (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
